value.value: An agent that antagonizes bombesin, an endogenous neurotransmitter found in many animals, and affects smooth muscle, gastrin secretion, and renal function.
This gene plays a role in signal transduction in hematopoietic cells.
Achaete-scute homolog 1 (236 aa, ~25 kDa) is encoded by the human ASCL1 gene. This protein plays a role in both transcriptional regulation and signal transduction.

label.value: Protein with Unknown or Unclassified Function

value.value: Encoded by Genes with Unknown or Unclassified Function, Proteins (or RNAs) with Unknown or Unclassified Function have currently unidentified or unspecified cellular functions. (NCI)
SH2B adaptor protein 2 (632 aa, ~68 kDa) is encoded by the human SH2B2 gene. This protein is involved in the modulation of receptor tyrosine kinase signaling pathways.
Adenomatous polyposis coli protein 2 (2303 aa, ~244 kDa) is encoded by the human APC2 gene. This protein is involved in the regulation of catenin beta-1 turnover.

A-kinase anchor protein 9 (3911 aa, ~454 kDa) is encoded by the human AKAP9 gene. This protein plays a role in the localization of signaling proteins, including protein kinases A, C and N, protein phosphatases PP1 and PP2A, phosphodiesterase 4D3, and chloride intracellular channel proteins.
A-kinase anchor protein 12 (1782 aa, ~191 kDa) is encoded by the human AKAP12 gene. This protein is involved in the localization of protein kinases A and C.
This gene plays a role in chromatin remodeling and transcriptional regulation.

A non-invasive imaging method that uses a thermal sensitive camera to capture a digital image based on heat radiating from the body. In trials for detection of breast cancer, computer-assisted interpretation of the digital image helps to determine whether a local abnormality in breast tissue temperature is present, which may indicate the presence of disease.

A-kinase anchor protein 13 (2813 aa, ~308 kDa) is encoded by the human AKAP13 gene. This protein is involved in adrenergic receptor signaling, EGFR-mediated signal transduction and guanine nucleotide exchange factor activity for transforming protein RhoA.

Any substance that inhibits cytidine triphosphate synthetase, an enzyme that catalyses the rate-limiting step in the synthesis of CTP. Inhibition of cytidine triphosphate synthetase interferes with DNA, RNA, and CTP biosynthesis and can cause cell cycle arrest.
Retinal dehydrogenase 2 (518 aa, ~57 kDa) is encoded by the human ALDH1A2 gene. This protein plays a role in retinol metabolism.
Aflatoxin B1 aldehyde reductase member 2 (359 aa, ~40 kDa) is encoded by the human AKR7A2 gene. This protein is involved in aldehyde metabolism.

label.value: Sister Chromatid Cohesion Protein PDS5 Homolog B

value.value: Sister chromatid cohesion protein PDS5 homolog B (1447 aa, ~165 kDa) is encoded by the human PDS5B gene. This protein plays a role in the regulation of both mitosis and cell proliferation.
Annexin A5 (320 aa, ~36 kDa) is encoded by the human ANXA5 gene. This protein plays a role in the inhibition of blood coagulation and the transmembrane transport of calcium.
Anti-Muellerian hormone type-2 receptor (573 aa, ~63 kDa) is encoded by the human AMHR2 gene. This protein plays a role in signaling, serine/threonine phosphorylation and ligand binding.

label.value: DNA-Directed RNA Polymerase I Subunit RPA34

value.value: DNA-directed RNA polymerase I subunit RPA34 (510 aa, ~55 kDa) is encoded by the human POLR1G gene. This protein plays a role in the transcription of DNA into RNA.
Arachidonate 15-lipoxygenase (662 aa, ~75 kDa) is encoded by the human ALOX15 gene. This protein plays a role in leukotriene metabolism.
Mesencephalic astrocyte-derived neurotrophic factor (179 aa, ~20 kDa) is encoded by the human MANF gene. This protein is involved in both the function and survival of dopaminergic neurons.
STAM-binding protein (424 aa, ~48 kDa) is encoded by the human STAMBP gene. This protein plays a role in both signaling and deubiquitination of 'Lys-63'-linked polyubiquitin chains.

Any substance that inhibits O6-Alkylguanine-DNA alkyltransferase, a DNA repair enzyme that catalyzes the removal of alkyl groups from DNA. Inhibition of O6-Alkylguanine-DNA alkyltransferase increases the effectiveness of DNA alkylating agents.

Rho-related GTP-binding protein RhoH (191 aa, ~21 kDa) is encoded by the human RHOH gene. This protein plays a role in the regulation of hematopoietic progenitor cell proliferation, differentiation, survival and migration.
Activated CDC42 kinase 1 (1038 aa, ~115 kDa) is encoded by the human TNK2 gene. This protein is involved in tyrosine phosphorylation, endocytosis and signal transduction.

An electron microscopic technique for producing images of a surface by scanning an electron beam over the sample and measuring the electronic interactions at the interface. This technique provides highly magnified images of surface morphology.
This gene plays a role in cartilage and bone formation. It is involved in cellular growth and proliferation.
Genes that code for growth factors.

Expressed in a variety of tissues, Transforming Growth Factor-Beta Family Genes encode Transforming Growth Factor-Beta, an autocrine growth factor that can act synergistically with TGF-alpha in embryonic development, cellular differentiation, hormone secretion, and immune function. There are at least three forms of TGF-beta: TGF-beta 1, TGF-beta 2, and TGF-beta 1.2. The latter is a heterodimer of TGF-beta 1 and TGF-beta 2. (NCI)
Bone morphogenetic protein 10 (424 aa, ~48 kDa) is encoded by the human BMP10 gene. This protein plays a role in both signal transduction and cardiac muscle cell proliferation.
This gene is involved in signal transduction during oogenesis.
Bone morphogenetic protein 15 (392 aa, ~45 kDa) is encoded by the human BMP15 gene. This protein is involved in ovarian follicle development.
This gene plays a role in bone formation via regulation of osteoblast differentiation. It is also involved in cell cycle regulation.

Any substance that inhibits cytidine deaminase, an enzyme that scavenges exogenous and endogenous cytidine and 2'-deoxycytidine for UMP synthesis. Inhibition of cytidine deaminase increases the biological half-life of cytidine-containing compounds.
Bone morphogenetic protein 2 (396 aa, ~45 kDa) is encoded by the human BMP2 gene. This protein plays a role in cartilage and bone formation.
This gene is involved in bone and cartilage formation. It plays a role in the negative regulation of bone density.
Bone morphogenetic protein 3 (472 aa, ~53 kDa) is encoded by the human BMP3 gene. This protein is involved in the regulation of bone formation and density.
This gene plays a role in the regulation of mesenchymal differentiation. It is involved in cartilage and bone formation.
Bone morphogenetic protein 5 (454 aa, ~52 kDa) is encoded by the human BMP5 gene. This protein plays a role in receptor signaling.
This gene plays a role in enchondral bone formation. It is also involved in promoting the growth of dendrites.
Bone morphogenetic protein 6 (513 aa, ~57 kDa) is encoded by the human BMP6 gene. This protein is involved in bone development.
This gene is involved in calcium regulation and bone homeostasis. It also plays a role in the control of cellular development and differentiation.
Bone morphogenetic protein 7 (431 aa, ~49 kDa) is encoded by the human BMP7 gene. This protein plays a role in both cellular differentiation and organogenesis.
This gene plays a role in calcium regulation and bone homeostasis. It is involved in cartilage and bone formation.
Substances that demonstrate efficacy in treating tumor induced hypercalcemia.
Bone morphogenetic protein 8B (402 aa, ~45 kDa) is encoded by the human BMP8B gene. This protein is involved in osteogenesis.
This gene is involved in T-cell activation and immune recognition.
This gene is involved in the initiation of T-cell activation.
This gene is involved in the stimulation of T-cells and in immune responses.

Receptor Serine/Threonine Kinase Genes encode receptor proteins that each bind to specific signaling factors causing a conformational and functional change in the ligand-bound receptor, altering its interaction with target molecules, increasing the receptor kinase activity, and leading to changes in cellular physiology through modification of the activity of one or more signal transduction pathways.
